.TH SHIT 1 "2026-06-15" "shit" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
shit \- a fast POSIX and bash compatible shell
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B shit
.RI [ options ]
.RI [ script
.RI [ argument ...]]
.br
.B shit
.B \-c
.I command
.RI [ argument ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B shit
is a fast POSIX and bash compatible shell. It runs an interactive prompt when
standard input is a terminal and no script is given, runs a script file named on
the command line, or runs a command string given with
.BR \-c .
Before a script runs, the default mood walks the parsed tree to fold constants,
prune dead branches, and report shellcheck-style diagnostics, so a malformed
construct is caught up front rather than half-run.
.SH MOODS
The shell runs under one of three moods that set how strict it is. The default
.B shit
mood is the strictest bash superset and it warns on the questionable constructs
through the analysis stage. The
.B bash
mood runs the bash extensions with the analysis stage off. The
.B sh
mood behaves like dash. The mood drives the nounset, pipefail, and failglob
strictness, the analysis stage, and the parser features.
.PP
A binary named or symlinked to
.BR sh ", " dash ", or " bash
picks the matching mood and turns diagnostics off. The
.B set --mood
builtin changes the mood at runtime, and a
.B set --mood
inside the rc sticks for the session. An explicit
.BR "set -u" ", " "set -o pipefail" ", or " "set -o failglob"
is the script's own ask and survives a later mood switch.
.SH OPTIONS
.SS Mood and startup
.TP
.BR \-M ", " \-\-mood =\fINAME\fR
Select the runtime mood, one of
.BR shit ", " bash ", or " sh .
.TP
.BR \-L ", " \-\-init\-moods =\fILIST\fR
Source the startup files for each listed mood, in order, given comma separated or
by repeating the flag. The
.B shit
flavor reads /etc/shitrc and ~/.shitrc, the
.B bash
flavor reads the bash rc and its completion, and the
.B sh
flavor reads the file named by ENV. Defaults to the value of
.BR \-\-mood .
.TP
.BR \-I ", " \-\-mimicry
Run a script whose shebang names a shell shit can emulate in-process in the
matching mood rather than launching the real shell, for speed.
.TP
.B \-\-dumb
Equivalent to
.BR "\-\-mood sh \-T \-\-no\-diagnostics" .
.TP
.BR \-p ", " \-\-privileged
Skip every startup config file, turned on automatically in the setuid or setgid
case.
.TP
.BI \-\-rcfile= FILE
Source FILE as the interactive rc instead of ~/.bashrc.
.SS Diagnostics
.TP
.BR \-W ", " \-\-force\-warnings
Keep the analysis stage but report every error as a warning and let the run
proceed.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-diagnostics
Skip the analysis stage so evaluation begins sooner.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-init\-diagnostics
Suppress diagnostics and warnings only while the startup files source, then
restore them for the prompt. Pairs with
.BR \-W .
.TP
.B \-\-list\-diagnostics
List the shellcheck-style checks the analysis stage reports, then exit.
.TP
.BR \-T ", " \-\-no\-completion
Disable interactive tab completion and ghost-text.
.TP
.B \-\-enable\-shitbox
Resolve the bundled shitbox utility names such as
.BR ls ", " mkdir ", and " cp
directly as commands, the same as
.BR "set \-o shitbox" .
.SS POSIX
.TP
.BR \-c " \fICOMMAND\fR"
Read commands from the string COMMAND.
.TP
.BR \-i ", " \-\-interactive
Force interactive mode.
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-stdin
Read commands from standard input.
.TP
.BR \-e ", " \-\-error\-exit
Exit on the first failing command.
.TP
.BR \-f ", " \-\-no\-glob
Disable pathname expansion.
.TP
.BR \-u ", " \-\-no\-unset
Treat an unset variable as an error.
.TP
.BR \-C ", " \-\-no\-clobber
Refuse to overwrite an existing file through a plain redirection.
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-no\-exec
Parse the script without running it.
.TP
.BR \-x ", " \-\-xtrace
Print each command after expansion.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Print each line as it is read.
.TP
.BR \-a ", " \-\-export\-all
Mark every later assignment for the environment.
.TP
.BR \-l ", " \-\-login
Run as a login shell.
.SS Information
.TP
.B \-\-help
Display the help message and exit.
.TP
.B \-\-version
Display the version and notices and exit.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-short\-version
Display the short version and exit.
.SS Debugging
.TP
.BR \-A ", " \-\-show\-ast
Print the syntax tree before executing each command.
.TP
.BR \-E ", " \-\-show\-exit\-code
Print the exit code after each command.
.TP
.BR \-R ", " \-\-show\-lexed\-words
Print the escape bitmap after each parsed command.
.TP
.B \-\-show\-optimizer\-state
Trace the analysis prepass decisions and print a located line for every node the
analysis stage eliminated to standard error, then a final summary.
.TP
.B \-\-show\-stats
Print per-command statistics.
.TP
.B \-\-show\-memory
Print a memory report at exit.
.TP
.BI \-X " LEVEL" "\fR, \fB\-\-debug\-logging=" LEVEL
Enable internal logging at LEVEL, one of
.BR info ", " debug ", or " all .
Compiled in only in a debug build.
.TP
.BI \-\-debug\-logging\-file= FILE
Append the debug log to FILE instead of standard error.
.SH RESCUE
When a flag in SHIT_FLAGS or in the argument list fails to parse and standard
input is a terminal, the shell enters rescue rather than exiting, so a removed
flag left in a config never locks the user out of a new pane. Rescue prints the
error, prints
.BR "shit: Entering rescue." ,
resets to default flags, skips the rc chain, and drops to an interactive prompt.
A non-interactive run keeps the usage exit.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B SHIT_FLAGS
Default flags applied before the command line, where a flag on the command line
still wins. The recommended value is
.BR "\-W \-I \-\-init\-moods=shit,bash" .
.TP
.B SHIT_HISTORY
The command history file, ~/.shit_history by default.
.TP
.B SHIT_DIRECTORY_HISTORY
The frecency store the z builtin ranks, ~/.shit_directory_history by default.
.TP
.B ENV
The startup file the sh flavor sources.
.TP
.B NO_COLOR
Turn color off in the prompt and the diagnostics when set.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/shitrc
The system rc the shit flavor sources.
.TP
.I ~/.shitrc
The user rc the shit flavor sources.
.TP
.I ~/.shit_history
The default command history file.
.TP
.I ~/.shit_directory_history
The default frecency store for the z builtin.
.SH SHITBOX
The
.B shitbox
builtin hosts a set of small bundled coreutilities, so a system with only a
compiler can run a configure and a make under shit.
.B "shitbox ls"
runs the bundled ls, and a name that is already a builtin, such as
.BR echo ,
routes to that builtin. With the
.B \-\-enable\-shitbox
flag or
.B "set \-o shitbox"
the utility names resolve directly as commands without the prefix, and a builtin
still wins over a utility while a utility wins over a program on PATH. A binary
whose name is a utility, such as a symlink named ls, acts as that utility. In
the default shit mood a bare utility name also falls back to the bundled utility
when PATH holds no binary of that name, so a missing system coreutil is filled
in, while a PATH binary still takes precedence.
.PP
The utilities are
.BR ls ", " ln ", " rm ", " mkdir ", " rmdir ", " cp ", " mv ", " cat ", "
.BR tee ", " touch ", " basename ", " dirname ", " realpath ", " du ", " head ", "
.BR tail ", " wc ", " seq ", " tr ", " grep ", " sort ", " uniq ", " sleep ", "
.BR env ", " yes ", " pkill ", " killall ", " ps ", " find ", " make ", "
.BR which ", and " whoami .
Each takes a small set of flags. The bundled make reads a Makefile, expands its
variables, and runs each recipe through the shell. It handles single-level
pattern rules such as
.B "%.o: %.c"
with the automatic variables $@, $<, and $^, and has no chained implicit rules
and no parallelism.
.PP
A few utilities follow their coreutils counterparts closely.
.B ls
lays the names out in columns sized to the terminal, falls back to one name per
line when the output is not a terminal, and prints the mode, owner, group, size,
and time under
.BR \-l .
.B sleep
accepts a unit suffix on each duration, s for seconds, m for minutes, h for
hours, and d for days, the word inf for an unbounded pause, and more than one
duration to sum.
.B "ps aux"
prints the owner, the process id, and the full command line of every process.
.B find
walks each path and prints every entry, with
.BR \-name ", " \-type ", " \-maxdepth ", and " \-mindepth
to filter the walk.
.SH SHIT BUILTINS
These builtins are unique to shit and have no counterpart in bash or dash.
.TP
.B calc
Evaluate each argument as an arithmetic expression and print the value of the
last one, with the same operators and located errors the shell arithmetic uses.
In the default mood it computes in 128 bits, so a result wider than a signed
64-bit integer prints in full, while the bash and posix moods keep the 64-bit
wrap.
.TP
.B bench
Run each command repeatedly as a measured child and print a summary of the wall
time, the peak resident set, and the available perf counters as mean, standard
deviation, and range. With more than one command it prints each later command
against the first as a relative speed.
.TP
.B z
Change to a frequently visited directory ranked by a frecency store at
~/.shit_directory_history, which weights each directory by its visit count and
how recently it was seen. The operands join into one query that matches a
directory by case insensitive substring.
.SH EXIT STATUS
The shell exits with the status of the last command it ran. A usage error such as
an unknown flag in a non-interactive run exits with status 2.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR bash (1),
.BR dash (1),
.BR sh (1)
